WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.622 --> 00:00:06.580
DANIEL PINK: All right.

00:00:06.580 --> 00:00:07.420
Thank you, Heath.

00:00:07.420 --> 00:00:08.670
Thank you guys for being here.

00:00:08.670 --> 00:00:11.590
So I'm eager to tell you
about this latest book,

00:00:11.590 --> 00:00:13.150
tell you why I
wrote it, and then

00:00:13.150 --> 00:00:16.360
give you some ideas from it
and then take some questions.

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:19.150
I wrote this book out of a
sense of frustration largely.

00:00:19.150 --> 00:00:22.330
I was making all kinds of
decisions in my own life

00:00:22.330 --> 00:00:24.610
about when to do things.

00:00:24.610 --> 00:00:25.630
When should I exercise?

00:00:25.630 --> 00:00:26.990
When should I do
this kind of work?

00:00:26.990 --> 00:00:28.120
What should I do
that kind of work?

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:29.380
When should I start a project?

00:00:29.380 --> 00:00:31.870
When should I abandon a
project that's not working?

00:00:31.870 --> 00:00:34.491
And I was making those decisions
in a very, very sloppy way.

00:00:34.491 --> 00:00:36.490
I felt that I can make
them in a more coherent--

00:00:36.490 --> 00:00:38.440
I wanted to make
them in a better way.

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:39.730
I looked around for guidance.

00:00:39.730 --> 00:00:43.616
It didn't exist, but
that got me curious.

00:00:43.616 --> 00:00:45.490
I've written some books
about social science.

00:00:45.490 --> 00:00:48.316
And I said, I wonder if there is
any research on this question?

00:00:48.316 --> 00:00:49.690
And it turned out
there was a lot

00:00:49.690 --> 00:00:50.950
of research on this question.

00:00:50.950 --> 00:00:53.370
It was in many, many fields--
literally dozens of fields.

00:00:53.370 --> 00:00:55.510
It was in economics
and social psychology,

00:00:55.510 --> 00:00:57.810
but it was also in
molecular biology.

00:00:57.810 --> 00:01:00.190
There's a whole field
of chronobiology.

00:01:00.190 --> 00:01:02.440
There is research
in anesthesiology,

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:04.450
endocrinology-- all
these different fields

00:01:04.450 --> 00:01:06.490
asking very similar questions.

00:01:06.490 --> 00:01:09.947
What's the effect of time of day
on what we do and how we do it?

00:01:09.947 --> 00:01:11.530
How do beginnings
affect our behavior?

00:01:11.530 --> 00:01:13.120
How do midpoints
affect our behavior?

00:01:13.120 --> 00:01:14.990
How do endings
affect our behavior?

00:01:14.990 --> 00:01:16.990
And I felt if you go wide
enough and deep enough

00:01:16.990 --> 00:01:19.990
into this research you can
begin to piece together

00:01:19.990 --> 00:01:22.990
the evidence-based ways to
make better, smarter, shorter

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:24.850
decisions about
when to do things.

00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:29.950
For you guys, what I did
is I just put together

00:01:29.950 --> 00:01:31.320
five questions.

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:34.390
I'm going to ask five
questions and then provide

00:01:34.390 --> 00:01:37.472
the answers to those questions
based on this research.

00:01:37.472 --> 00:01:39.013
But the main idea
here-- and then I'm

00:01:39.013 --> 00:01:41.137
going to spend a lot of
time taking your questions.

00:01:41.137 --> 00:01:43.630
The main idea here is that we
think that timing is an art,

00:01:43.630 --> 00:01:44.917
but it's really a science.

00:01:44.917 --> 00:01:46.750
We don't have to make
these timing decisions

00:01:46.750 --> 00:01:50.560
in such a haphazard, intuitive,
guesswork-centered way.

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:54.320
We can make them in a better,
smarter, more systematic way.

00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:56.200
So let's talk about five.

00:01:56.200 --> 00:01:59.920
I'm talking five very specific,
nitty-gritty questions about

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:01.180
timing--

00:02:01.180 --> 00:02:04.820
all kinds of different things,
fairly idiosyncratic list here.

00:02:04.820 --> 00:02:07.210
So number one-- at
what time of day

00:02:07.210 --> 00:02:09.720
should Alphabet hold its
quarterly earnings calls?

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:11.830
Alphabet holds its
earnings calls at 1:30

00:02:11.830 --> 00:02:14.230
Pacific, 4:30 Eastern.

00:02:14.230 --> 00:02:16.180
Is that a good idea?

00:02:16.180 --> 00:02:19.550
Does it matter at what
time of day we do things?

00:02:19.550 --> 00:02:20.710
Does it matter a little?

00:02:20.710 --> 00:02:22.087
Does it matter a lot?

00:02:22.087 --> 00:02:23.170
Let's find out, all right?

00:02:23.170 --> 00:02:24.919
There's a huge amount
of research on this.

00:02:24.919 --> 00:02:27.350
This is just one
tiny little nugget.

00:02:27.350 --> 00:02:31.010
And as many of you know,
there's some incredible insights

00:02:31.010 --> 00:02:33.340
one can get from big data now.

00:02:33.340 --> 00:02:36.257
I don't need to explain
all that to you.

00:02:36.257 --> 00:02:37.840
One of the really
interesting programs

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:40.470
being used in big data research
is something called LIWC--

00:02:40.470 --> 00:02:43.310
L-I-W-C-- the Linguistic
Inquiry Word Count.

00:02:43.310 --> 00:02:46.500
It's basically a
gigantic text analyzer.

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:49.260
It can take a giant body of
text or a small body of text

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:51.660
and do all kinds of analysis
that would otherwise

00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:53.670
take an army of people to do.

00:02:53.670 --> 00:02:56.050
So these researchers at NYU--

00:02:56.050 --> 00:02:59.760
so there's been
research on tracking.

00:02:59.760 --> 00:03:01.590
You can actually have
a pretty good read

00:03:01.590 --> 00:03:04.860
on the patterns of mood
over the course of a day

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:08.820
by analyzing tweets,
because the program

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:11.290
can measure the emotional
valence of the words there.

00:03:11.290 --> 00:03:16.070
You can do all kinds of
things with this, including

00:03:16.070 --> 00:03:19.010
measuring any body of text.

00:03:19.010 --> 00:03:20.880
So here's a body of text--

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:23.515
26,000 corporate earnings calls.

00:03:23.515 --> 00:03:25.640
All these corporate earnings
calls are transcribed.

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:28.200
You guys put them on your site--

00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:31.020
the transcriptions of all
of your earnings calls.

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:34.960
These researchers at NYU
took these 26,000 calls

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:37.100
from 2,100 companies
over 6 and 1/2 years.

00:03:37.100 --> 00:03:41.089
Now, just think about manually
reading through 26,000

00:03:41.089 --> 00:03:42.130
corporate earnings calls.

00:03:42.130 --> 00:03:44.380
You would want to just beat
your head against the wall

00:03:44.380 --> 00:03:45.400
after about five, right?

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:48.410
And so they were actually
looking for something else.

00:03:48.410 --> 00:03:51.790
And they said, does
the emotional content

00:03:51.790 --> 00:03:55.150
of the words being used
in these earnings calls

00:03:55.150 --> 00:03:59.125
both by the executives
who are leading it

00:03:59.125 --> 00:04:00.750
and by the analysts
and journalists who

00:04:00.750 --> 00:04:02.400
are asking questions--
does the mood

00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:06.730
change at all based
on time of day?

00:04:06.730 --> 00:04:11.560
And the answer was,
yeah, even when

00:04:11.560 --> 00:04:14.180
you control for fundamentals--

00:04:14.180 --> 00:04:17.649
even when you control
for fundamentals, right?

00:04:17.649 --> 00:04:19.300
Here's what happened.

00:04:19.300 --> 00:04:22.420
Afternoon calls were
more negative, irritable,

00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:24.910
and combative, leading to--

00:04:24.910 --> 00:04:26.470
here's the punch
line right here--

00:04:26.470 --> 00:04:31.330
temporary stock mispricings
for firms hosting earnings

00:04:31.330 --> 00:04:33.882
calls later in the day.

00:04:33.882 --> 00:04:35.340
Now, think about
that for a second.

00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:37.027
That's kind of weird, right?

00:04:37.027 --> 00:04:38.110
It doesn't make any sense.

00:04:38.110 --> 00:04:38.735
Think about it.

00:04:38.735 --> 00:04:40.890
You guys are familiar
with earnings calls.

00:04:40.890 --> 00:04:42.720
The people who do
your earnings calls--

00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:44.460
your CEO and your CFO--

00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:46.810
what's your CEO's first name?

00:04:46.810 --> 00:04:48.190
Sundar, right?

00:04:48.190 --> 00:04:48.690
OK, right.

00:04:48.690 --> 00:04:50.880
And then your CFO is Ruth.

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:52.955
So are Sundar and
Ruth pretty good?

00:04:52.955 --> 00:04:54.420
Are they any good?

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:56.460
They know what they're
doing more or less?

00:04:56.460 --> 00:05:00.380
You're being videotaped,
but you know.

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:02.130
They know what they're
doing more or less?

00:05:02.130 --> 00:05:02.730
OK.

00:05:02.730 --> 00:05:05.640
Do you think those guys prepare
for these earnings calls?

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:07.890
Any of you ever been involved
in anything like that?

00:05:07.890 --> 00:05:09.360
They prepare like
crazy-- not just

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:12.300
these two but any CFO and CEO.

00:05:12.300 --> 00:05:13.620
They prepare like crazy.

00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:14.674
They have talking points.

00:05:14.674 --> 00:05:15.840
They rehearse the questions.

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:16.965
They're very well prepared.

00:05:16.965 --> 00:05:19.980
Do Sundar and Ruth have anything
at stake in these earnings

00:05:19.980 --> 00:05:21.120
calls?

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:23.800
What?

00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:24.300
Repetition.

00:05:24.300 --> 00:05:25.385
What else?

00:05:25.385 --> 00:05:26.760
You can say it--
personal wealth.

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:27.840
Exactly.

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:28.440
All right.

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:30.060
So here you have--

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:36.520
and just extrapolate to how
many companies were there?

00:05:36.520 --> 00:05:37.590
2,100 companies.

00:05:37.590 --> 00:05:40.930
Extrapolate to 2,000 companies.

00:05:40.930 --> 00:05:43.710
Their CEOs and CFOs
know what they're doing.

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:44.780
They're well prepared.

00:05:44.780 --> 00:05:46.100
They have something at stake.

00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:48.710
And yet time of
day had an effect

00:05:48.710 --> 00:05:50.660
on the mood of these
calls to the point

00:05:50.660 --> 00:05:53.900
where the stocks for
afternoon conference calls

00:05:53.900 --> 00:05:55.686
were temporarily mispriced.

00:05:55.686 --> 00:05:57.560
And I'm convinced there's
someone out there--

00:05:57.560 --> 00:05:59.300
maybe even in this building--

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:02.200
who has written a
program to exploit

00:06:02.200 --> 00:06:05.000
that delta between
the true price

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:07.550
and the misprice
because of time of day.

00:06:07.550 --> 00:06:09.690
And over and over
and over again,

00:06:09.690 --> 00:06:12.590
we see this in the research--
over and over and over again.

00:06:12.590 --> 00:06:14.090
Here's what we know.

00:06:14.090 --> 00:06:16.619
Our mood does not stay the
same throughout the day.

00:06:16.619 --> 00:06:18.410
Our cognitive abilities
don't stay the same

00:06:18.410 --> 00:06:19.460
throughout the day.

00:06:19.460 --> 00:06:20.960
Our mood and our
cognitive abilities

00:06:20.960 --> 00:06:22.640
change throughout the day.

00:06:22.640 --> 00:06:24.890
They change in predictable
ways, and they sometimes

00:06:24.890 --> 00:06:26.720
can change in dramatic ways.

00:06:29.540 --> 00:06:31.000
Let me tell you what that means.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:32.500
Basically what we know is this.

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:34.630
We tend to move through
the day in three stages--

00:06:34.630 --> 00:06:37.870
peak, trough, recovery,
peak, trough, recovery.

00:06:37.870 --> 00:06:41.920
In general, our mood
goes up, then it dips,

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:43.460
then it goes back up again.

00:06:43.460 --> 00:06:45.100
And that has an
effect on performance,

00:06:45.100 --> 00:06:46.930
and performance
varies more than you

00:06:46.930 --> 00:06:48.650
would think over time of day.

00:06:48.650 --> 00:06:50.620
I'll give you an
example of that--

00:06:50.620 --> 00:06:52.519
hospitals.

00:06:52.519 --> 00:06:54.560
If you learn nothing else
from our little session

00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:57.860
here this morning, don't go to
the hospital in the afternoon

00:06:57.860 --> 00:06:59.890
if you can avoid it.

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:01.750
There are predictable
differences

00:07:01.750 --> 00:07:04.540
in hospital performance
based on time of day.

00:07:04.540 --> 00:07:08.200
Example-- anesthesia errors--

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:13.350
four times more likely at
3:00 PM than at 9:00 AM.

00:07:13.350 --> 00:07:16.440
hand washing in hospitals-- huge
deterioration in hand washing

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:20.805
at hospitals in the afternoon.

00:07:20.805 --> 00:07:21.430
It's lunchtime.

00:07:21.430 --> 00:07:24.280
Let's talk about colonoscopies.

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:27.910
Colonoscopies-- doctors
find half as many polyps

00:07:27.910 --> 00:07:31.380
in afternoon exams as
they do in morning exams.

00:07:31.380 --> 00:07:34.066
Unnecessary antibiotics
fueling the rise of superbugs--

00:07:34.066 --> 00:07:35.440
much more likely
to be prescribed

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:40.587
in the afternoon
versus the morning.

00:07:40.587 --> 00:07:41.670
You see it in health care.

00:07:41.670 --> 00:07:42.610
You see it in education.

00:07:42.610 --> 00:07:43.984
There's a great
piece of research

00:07:43.984 --> 00:07:47.610
from the University of Chicago
looking at 2 million students

00:07:47.610 --> 00:07:51.130
from the LA Unified
School District.

00:07:51.130 --> 00:07:54.230
Students who took
math in the morning

00:07:54.230 --> 00:07:58.140
had better GPAs, higher
test scores than students

00:07:58.140 --> 00:07:59.940
who took math in the afternoon.

00:07:59.940 --> 00:08:02.644
Over and over and over
again we see this pattern.

00:08:02.644 --> 00:08:03.810
Here's what we need to know.

00:08:03.810 --> 00:08:06.390
Our cognitive abilities
don't remain the same

00:08:06.390 --> 00:08:08.220
over the course of the day.

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:09.330
They change.

00:08:09.330 --> 00:08:11.010
They change in predictable ways.

00:08:11.010 --> 00:08:13.140
They sometimes change
in dramatic ways,

00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:15.330
and the right time
to do something

00:08:15.330 --> 00:08:17.082
depends on what you're doing.

00:08:17.082 --> 00:08:18.540
We can talk more
about that in Q&amp;A,

00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:22.300
because I'm going to
be pretty brief here.

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:25.470
Another question about
the particular tactical--

00:08:25.470 --> 00:08:28.260
just put basically a dog's
breakfast of tactical questions

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:31.250
about timing.

00:08:31.250 --> 00:08:35.780
Two-- when should you ask
your boss for a raise?

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:37.590
When should you ask
your boss for a raise?

00:08:37.590 --> 00:08:38.710
What time of day do
you think you should

00:08:38.710 --> 00:08:39.793
ask your boss for a raise?

00:08:39.793 --> 00:08:40.730
AUDIENCE: After lunch.

00:08:40.730 --> 00:08:41.659
DANIEL PINK: After lunch.

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:41.870
OK.

00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:42.453
Good instinct.

00:08:42.453 --> 00:08:43.610
What makes you say that?

00:08:43.610 --> 00:08:46.837
AUDIENCE: They're happy
that they've eaten.

00:08:46.837 --> 00:08:50.450
DANIEL PINK: They're happy that
they've eaten a free meal, OK?

00:08:50.450 --> 00:08:51.410
That's a good instinct.

00:08:51.410 --> 00:08:52.472
Tell me your first name.

00:08:52.472 --> 00:08:53.180
AUDIENCE: Amelia.

00:08:53.180 --> 00:08:53.750
DANIEL PINK: Amelia.

00:08:53.750 --> 00:08:54.170
All right.

00:08:54.170 --> 00:08:55.220
So let's take a look at this.

00:08:55.220 --> 00:08:56.470
Here's what we're going to do.

00:08:56.470 --> 00:08:59.780
We're going to analogize
to some research--

00:08:59.780 --> 00:09:03.870
very powerful pretty well-known
research out of Israel.

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:07.775
This is a study done of judges--

00:09:07.775 --> 00:09:11.380
a study done of parole hearings.

00:09:11.380 --> 00:09:14.860
You'll see why this matters.

00:09:14.860 --> 00:09:17.460
These judges come before--

00:09:17.460 --> 00:09:19.930
you have prisoners in Israel
who come before these judges,

00:09:19.930 --> 00:09:23.290
and these judges decide
whether they get parole.

00:09:23.290 --> 00:09:25.960
Do they stay in prison for
the rest of their term?

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:28.920
Do they get early release?

00:09:28.920 --> 00:09:30.730
Do they continue wearing
an ankle monitor,

00:09:30.730 --> 00:09:33.160
or are they allowed
to remove it?

00:09:33.160 --> 00:09:38.350
These are pretty significant
decisions about human liberty.

00:09:38.350 --> 00:09:42.360
Does time of day effect
those judicial decisions?

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:44.370
And the answer is--

00:09:44.370 --> 00:09:46.640
what do you think the answer is?

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:48.710
Why else would I be
mentioning it, right?

00:09:48.710 --> 00:09:50.820
I want you to take a
look at this chart here.

00:09:50.820 --> 00:09:52.490
This is a chart.

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:57.170
On the vertical axis is your
probability of getting paroled.

00:09:57.170 --> 00:09:59.300
The horizontal axis
is time of day.

00:09:59.300 --> 00:10:03.350
Early in the day, you've got
a pretty good chance, then big

00:10:03.350 --> 00:10:04.130
drop.

00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:07.040
Then-- Amelia's instincts
were very good--

00:10:07.040 --> 00:10:08.450
the judge has a break.

00:10:08.450 --> 00:10:12.170
It goes back up
then way back down.

00:10:12.170 --> 00:10:17.660
Then the judge has a
break, then way back up.

00:10:17.660 --> 00:10:19.440
Now think about
this for a second.

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:23.150
Remember, your timing of when
you appear before that judge is

00:10:23.150 --> 00:10:26.570
largely random, right?

00:10:26.570 --> 00:10:28.490
It's like going to the DMV.

00:10:28.490 --> 00:10:32.499
How long is a person
waiting in line?

00:10:32.499 --> 00:10:34.790
I guess nobody here owns a
car, so let's make something

00:10:34.790 --> 00:10:36.080
more relevant to your life.

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:38.277
You're waiting in line
at Whole Foods, OK?

00:10:38.277 --> 00:10:39.860
You're waiting in
line at Whole Foods.

00:10:39.860 --> 00:10:45.050
How long it takes depends
on who's in front of you--

00:10:45.050 --> 00:10:46.554
how long that takes.

00:10:46.554 --> 00:10:48.470
You don't know when
you're going to get taken.

00:10:48.470 --> 00:10:49.636
So take a look at that here.

00:10:49.636 --> 00:10:52.100
So imagine your loved one is
coming in for a parole hearing

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:55.880
immediately before
the judge has a break.

00:10:55.880 --> 00:10:57.330
Your odds are not good.

00:10:57.330 --> 00:10:59.390
And then imagine
the schmo behind--

00:10:59.390 --> 00:11:01.310
the next person in
line, the person

00:11:01.310 --> 00:11:05.570
who had ticket number 14 versus
ticket number 13 in the order--

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:07.500
comes in after the
judge has their break.

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:14.400
There's like a seven
or eight x difference.

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:17.230
So what does this have
to do with your boss?

00:11:17.230 --> 00:11:20.610
Here's what it has
to do with your boss.

00:11:20.610 --> 00:11:23.980
When we make decisions--
human beings make decisions--

00:11:23.980 --> 00:11:26.520
So first of all, this should
scare the hell out of us

00:11:26.520 --> 00:11:29.350
about the criminal
justice system.

00:11:29.350 --> 00:11:30.600
There other things about this.

00:11:33.439 --> 00:11:34.980
There's a great book
that I recommend

00:11:34.980 --> 00:11:37.770
to you called "Unfair" by a
guy named Adam Benforado who's

00:11:37.770 --> 00:11:39.930
a professor at
Temple Law School.

00:11:39.930 --> 00:11:42.270
And it basically makes
this very powerful argument

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:44.640
that much of our
justice system is

00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:47.100
built on assumptions
and premises

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:50.730
about human behavior
that are not true.

00:11:50.730 --> 00:11:52.210
That's problematic.

00:11:52.210 --> 00:11:54.049
And so this might
be another example.

00:11:54.049 --> 00:11:55.590
I'll give you another
example of time

00:11:55.590 --> 00:11:58.230
of day effects on
juror decision making.

00:11:58.230 --> 00:11:59.787
This is experimental research.

00:11:59.787 --> 00:12:00.620
Here's what they do.

00:12:00.620 --> 00:12:02.620
They have a fact
pattern, all right?

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:03.995
So here's what
we're going to do.

00:12:03.995 --> 00:12:05.850
I got a fact pattern
about a defendant.

00:12:05.850 --> 00:12:09.210
And I'm going to give this
group this fact pattern,

00:12:09.210 --> 00:12:12.189
and I'm going to give this
group this fact pattern.

00:12:12.189 --> 00:12:14.730
I'm going to describe to you a
defendant and all the evidence

00:12:14.730 --> 00:12:16.540
about that defendant.

00:12:16.540 --> 00:12:17.790
You get the same fact pattern.

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:19.040
You get the same fact pattern.

00:12:19.040 --> 00:12:22.710
The only difference is that
this group, the defendant's name

00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:24.900
is Robert Garner,
and in this group,

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:28.060
the defendant's name
is Roberto Garcia--

00:12:28.060 --> 00:12:30.100
same exact facts though.

00:12:30.100 --> 00:12:33.340
When jurors deliberated
in the morning,

00:12:33.340 --> 00:12:35.440
both defendants are
treated the same way.

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:37.760
When jurors deliberated
in the afternoon,

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:40.870
they were more likely to
exonerate Garner and convict

00:12:40.870 --> 00:12:43.830
Garcia on the same set of facts.

00:12:43.830 --> 00:12:44.680
Yeah.

00:12:44.680 --> 00:12:46.300
So we should be
disturbed about this

00:12:46.300 --> 00:12:47.900
for a number of
different reasons.

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:50.830
But let's take this back to
decision making writ large.

00:12:50.830 --> 00:12:52.930
When people make decisions--

00:12:52.930 --> 00:12:54.520
anybody makes a
decision-- they come

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:57.040
to that decision with,
in their back pocket,

00:12:57.040 --> 00:12:58.660
a default decision.

00:12:58.660 --> 00:13:00.970
And that decision is largely no.

00:13:00.970 --> 00:13:02.792
Anybody here in sales?

00:13:02.792 --> 00:13:03.700
OK, yeah.

00:13:03.700 --> 00:13:05.147
So when you go to
pitch a prospect

00:13:05.147 --> 00:13:07.480
or something like that, you
know what I'm talking about.

00:13:07.480 --> 00:13:09.401
The default decision
is no, right?

00:13:09.401 --> 00:13:10.900
You go to ask your
boss for a raise.

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:12.257
The default decision is no.

00:13:12.257 --> 00:13:13.840
You go to ask somebody
out for a date.

00:13:13.840 --> 00:13:17.140
The default decision is no-- at
least that was my experience.

00:13:20.410 --> 00:13:22.990
And when parole
judges make decisions,

00:13:22.990 --> 00:13:24.310
the default answer is no.

00:13:24.310 --> 00:13:29.170
Remember, if a judge doesn't
grant parole, she's fine.

00:13:29.170 --> 00:13:31.960
If a judge grants parole and
that person she's paroled

00:13:31.960 --> 00:13:33.790
goes on to do
something horrible,

00:13:33.790 --> 00:13:35.800
that's really bad for her.

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:38.020
So the default decision
is not to grant parole.

00:13:38.020 --> 00:13:40.750
What we see over and over again
in studies of decision making

00:13:40.750 --> 00:13:41.710
is the following.

00:13:41.710 --> 00:13:47.140
People are more likely to
overcome the default early

00:13:47.140 --> 00:13:49.990
in the day and
immediately after breaks--

00:13:49.990 --> 00:13:52.180
early in the day and
immediately after breaks.

00:13:52.180 --> 00:13:54.970
So Amelia, you were
exactly right about that.

00:13:54.970 --> 00:13:57.100
Hit your boss after
lunch if you want

00:13:57.100 --> 00:13:59.920
