00:30:30.830 --> 00:30:32.538
that you're not at
your best at 9 o'clock

00:30:32.538 --> 00:30:35.420
in the morning, which
is totally cool.

00:30:35.420 --> 00:30:38.720
Here's what I recommend you do.

00:30:38.720 --> 00:30:43.070
The day before you have an
important 9:00 meeting--

00:30:43.070 --> 00:30:46.130
say you're working between
7:00 and 10:00 PM--

00:30:46.130 --> 00:30:48.110
here's what I
recommend that you do.

00:30:48.110 --> 00:30:49.880
Make a checklist
for what you want

00:30:49.880 --> 00:30:50.870
to say at that
meeting, what you want

00:30:50.870 --> 00:30:51.960
to accomplish at that
meeting, what you need

00:30:51.960 --> 00:30:53.126
to get done at that meeting.

00:30:53.126 --> 00:30:55.310
Any questions you need to ask--

00:30:55.310 --> 00:30:57.020
make that checklist.

00:30:57.020 --> 00:30:59.790
And actually come into the
meeting with that checklist

00:30:59.790 --> 00:31:02.570
so you don't have to
draw on your hazy mind

00:31:02.570 --> 00:31:04.057
when you're at your worst.

00:31:04.057 --> 00:31:06.390
Figure out what you want to
do when you're at your best,

00:31:06.390 --> 00:31:08.330
and then give yourself
those guidelines

00:31:08.330 --> 00:31:10.520
to rely on when
you're at your worst.

00:31:10.520 --> 00:31:13.244
The other thing that I would
absolutely recommend is--

00:31:13.244 --> 00:31:14.660
and this goes to
the whole chapter

00:31:14.660 --> 00:31:17.690
that I have on breaks-- is
before that 9:00 meeting,

00:31:17.690 --> 00:31:19.370
take a walk around the block.

00:31:19.370 --> 00:31:22.670
Movement, sunlight, nature--
take a walk around the block.

00:31:22.670 --> 00:31:25.640
The other thing-- someone
here mentioned gratitude,

00:31:25.640 --> 00:31:27.720
and there's a first
cousin of this.

00:31:32.090 --> 00:31:34.000
Doing a good deed
for somebody else

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:36.320
is a pretty significant
mood booster.

00:31:36.320 --> 00:31:39.630
So maybe bring somebody a cup
of coffee or help somebody

00:31:39.630 --> 00:31:41.130
move something--
that kind of thing.

00:31:41.130 --> 00:31:43.242
So go into that 9:00
meeting with your checklist.

00:31:43.242 --> 00:31:45.200
Before you do it, take
a walk around the block.

00:31:45.200 --> 00:31:46.670
Maybe do somebody a good deed.

00:31:46.670 --> 00:31:48.330
You're going to be
a little bit better.

00:31:48.330 --> 00:31:50.270
And the key here that
I want to emphasize,

00:31:50.270 --> 00:31:52.879
not only the
individual variation--

00:31:52.879 --> 00:31:54.920
the fact that science
gives us these broad design

00:31:54.920 --> 00:32:04.396
principles-- but
individual variation

00:32:04.396 --> 00:32:06.020
is going to play a
role in all of this.

00:32:12.225 --> 00:32:14.550
You really have to get better--

00:32:14.550 --> 00:32:16.800
what we're talking about
here is not like, oh, my God,

00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:18.180
you're going to be a
superstar in every meeting

00:32:18.180 --> 00:32:19.931
now at 9:00 in the
morning if you do this.

00:32:19.931 --> 00:32:21.263
Here's what we're talking about.

00:32:21.263 --> 00:32:23.380
We're talking about this
in a probabilistic way.

00:32:23.380 --> 00:32:25.170
So let's say that you have--

00:32:27.930 --> 00:32:30.040
for you going to
a 9:00 AM meeting,

00:32:30.040 --> 00:32:32.490
you have a 23% chance of
getting good work done,

00:32:32.490 --> 00:32:34.950
getting good stuff accomplished.

00:32:34.950 --> 00:32:36.360
And if you do
these other things,

00:32:36.360 --> 00:32:41.178
we can dial that
up to a 28% chance.

00:32:41.178 --> 00:32:43.320
There's still a 72% chance
this meeting is going

00:32:43.320 --> 00:32:45.420
to be a bomb, Chris, right?

00:32:45.420 --> 00:32:49.890
But I'll take that
turn from 24%--

00:32:49.890 --> 00:32:51.870
whatever I said-- to
28%, because you're

00:32:51.870 --> 00:32:53.864
going to go to a lot
of meetings, right?

00:32:53.864 --> 00:32:55.780
Over and over and over,
that's going to do it.

00:32:55.780 --> 00:32:56.820
So what we're
talking about here is

00:32:56.820 --> 00:32:58.712
turning the dial in
our favor a little bit

00:32:58.712 --> 00:33:01.170
using some of these principles
and the individual variation

00:33:01.170 --> 00:33:02.430
that we notice in ourselves.

00:33:02.430 --> 00:33:03.130
Who else has a question?

00:33:03.130 --> 00:33:04.505
Because I get to
throw something.

00:33:04.505 --> 00:33:05.640
All right, back there.

00:33:05.640 --> 00:33:08.700
How heavy is this?

00:33:08.700 --> 00:33:09.780
Ooh.

00:33:09.780 --> 00:33:12.077
That was my slider.

00:33:12.077 --> 00:33:12.660
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:33:12.660 --> 00:33:14.400
So I noticed that,
yeah, I'm much more

00:33:14.400 --> 00:33:16.260
productive in the mornings.

00:33:16.260 --> 00:33:18.900
And also doctors
and dentists are all

00:33:18.900 --> 00:33:20.730
more productive in the morning.

00:33:20.730 --> 00:33:23.010
So traditionally I've always
scheduled my appointments

00:33:23.010 --> 00:33:25.440
in the afternoon, that way
I'm most productive at work.

00:33:25.440 --> 00:33:28.136
And then I go to visit
them in the afternoon.

00:33:28.136 --> 00:33:29.510
But what you're
showing now would

00:33:29.510 --> 00:33:30.960
be you should actually
try to visit them

00:33:30.960 --> 00:33:31.890
in the middle of the day.

00:33:31.890 --> 00:33:34.110
But that means that impacts
my productivity, because I'm

00:33:34.110 --> 00:33:35.040
working in the afternoon.

00:33:35.040 --> 00:33:36.873
So have you kind of
thought about that trade

00:33:36.873 --> 00:33:39.069
off of optimizing
yours versus others?

00:33:39.069 --> 00:33:40.110
DANIEL PINK: Great point.

00:33:40.110 --> 00:33:46.087
Great point, particularly
on medical appointments.

00:33:46.087 --> 00:33:46.920
So here's the thing.

00:33:46.920 --> 00:33:50.970
If it's a significant
medical appointment,

00:33:50.970 --> 00:33:53.070
I would pay the price
of my own productivity

00:33:53.070 --> 00:33:54.090
and go in the morning.

00:33:54.090 --> 00:33:56.400
So for my own family, when
there's something important

00:33:56.400 --> 00:33:59.650
going on-- a visit
to a hospital--

00:33:59.650 --> 00:34:03.822
my elder daughter at age 20
had her wisdom teeth taken out.

00:34:03.822 --> 00:34:05.280
She had to have
general anesthesia.

00:34:05.280 --> 00:34:07.380
No way in hell she's
going in the afternoon

00:34:07.380 --> 00:34:08.370
to that appointment.

00:34:08.370 --> 00:34:09.060
I mean that.

00:34:09.060 --> 00:34:11.340
I'm dead serious about that.

00:34:11.340 --> 00:34:15.124
For things serious, nobody in
my family goes in the afternoon

00:34:15.124 --> 00:34:15.719
now.

00:34:15.719 --> 00:34:20.400
The numbers are
that overwhelming,

00:34:20.400 --> 00:34:24.109
so I put a heavy weight on that.

00:34:24.109 --> 00:34:25.650
I'll give you an
example of something

00:34:25.650 --> 00:34:28.590
that I do literally
schedule in the afternoon--

00:34:28.590 --> 00:34:30.610
a routine dental visit.

00:34:30.610 --> 00:34:32.497
It's going to be fine.

00:34:32.497 --> 00:34:35.781
It's pretty simple
and straightforward.

00:34:35.781 --> 00:34:37.489
I don't have any
serious dental problems.

00:34:37.489 --> 00:34:38.960
They're just going to
do a cleaning and X-rays

00:34:38.960 --> 00:34:39.850
and whatever.

00:34:39.850 --> 00:34:41.810
They can probably do
that reasonably well,

00:34:41.810 --> 00:34:43.900
and it's not worth
getting a tiny little bit

00:34:43.900 --> 00:34:49.150
advantage of slightly,
infinitesimally cleaner teeth

00:34:49.150 --> 00:34:51.946
and sacrifice my best
work period of the day.

00:34:51.946 --> 00:34:53.320
So it's that kind
of a trade off.

00:34:53.320 --> 00:34:54.670
But for anything significant?

00:34:54.670 --> 00:34:55.270
No way.

00:34:55.270 --> 00:34:55.780
Go in the morning.

00:34:55.780 --> 00:34:56.560
I'm dead serious.

00:34:56.560 --> 00:34:58.810
Go in the morning.

00:34:58.810 --> 00:35:01.220
I don't even think
it's a close call.

00:35:01.220 --> 00:35:01.900
Yes sir.

00:35:01.900 --> 00:35:04.640
Oh, sorry.

00:35:04.640 --> 00:35:07.580
AUDIENCE: Similar to that, have
you thought about time zones?

00:35:07.580 --> 00:35:09.917
Because then the trade
off is interesting.

00:35:09.917 --> 00:35:11.750
Let's say you have a
meeting or an interview

00:35:11.750 --> 00:35:13.310
with somebody in London.

00:35:13.310 --> 00:35:16.920
Do you optimize for their time,
or do you optimize for yours?

00:35:16.920 --> 00:35:18.320
DANIEL PINK: It's really hard.

00:35:18.320 --> 00:35:20.166
It depends on the meeting
and to some extent

00:35:20.166 --> 00:35:21.040
who's more important.

00:35:21.040 --> 00:35:27.100
So if you have an
important customer,

00:35:27.100 --> 00:35:29.600
I would take the hit yourself
and optimize for the customer.

00:35:29.600 --> 00:35:31.520
Make it the
customer's best time.

00:35:31.520 --> 00:35:33.350
If you're talking
about distributed teams

00:35:33.350 --> 00:35:36.399
within Google,
Alphabet, then I think

00:35:36.399 --> 00:35:37.940
it becomes a little
more complicated.

00:35:37.940 --> 00:35:40.790
Because remember, let's
take a step back here.

00:35:40.790 --> 00:35:43.940
Think about our brains.

00:35:43.940 --> 00:35:49.910
Our brains evolved in a world
where there were not hours

00:35:49.910 --> 00:35:52.610
let alone time zones.

00:35:52.610 --> 00:35:55.340
It is completely
unnatural for our brain

00:35:55.340 --> 00:35:59.940
to be talking to someone who is
literally in a different day,

00:35:59.940 --> 00:36:00.440
right?

00:36:03.260 --> 00:36:06.300
Our brains aren't wired
to do that kind of thing,

00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:07.110
so it's very hard.

00:36:07.110 --> 00:36:10.190
So if you have these distributed
teams as is very, very common,

00:36:10.190 --> 00:36:13.550
I think there are probably two
solutions-- not even solutions.

00:36:13.550 --> 00:36:14.960
There are two responses to that.

00:36:14.960 --> 00:36:16.850
I think the meta
thing is recognizing

00:36:16.850 --> 00:36:20.660
we are not built to do that,
so it's going to be very hard.

00:36:20.660 --> 00:36:23.490
I think the key thing to do
tactically are the following.

00:36:23.490 --> 00:36:27.077
One-- when we think about
that conference call--

00:36:27.077 --> 00:36:29.660
I imagine everybody in this room
has been in a conference call

00:36:29.660 --> 00:36:32.390
where somebody is in Asia,
and somebody is in Europe,

00:36:32.390 --> 00:36:36.792
and somebody is here--
multi-continent kinds of calls.

00:36:36.792 --> 00:36:38.750
I think what you have to
do is, before you even

00:36:38.750 --> 00:36:41.100
schedule that call,
you have to say,

00:36:41.100 --> 00:36:42.950
what are we trying
to accomplish?

00:36:42.950 --> 00:36:47.690
And what, if anything, can
be done asynchronously?

00:36:47.690 --> 00:36:49.162
If you think about a call--

00:36:49.162 --> 00:36:50.120
a meeting of any kind--

00:36:50.120 --> 00:36:53.840
it's basically a series of tasks
to be done, questions to ask,

00:36:53.840 --> 00:36:54.680
tasks to be done.

00:36:54.680 --> 00:36:56.630
So you have this bucket
of tasks to be done.

00:36:56.630 --> 00:36:58.296
You've got to look
inside of that bucket

00:36:58.296 --> 00:37:01.100
and say, do all these things
need to be done synchronously?

00:37:01.100 --> 00:37:02.460
And they usually don't.

00:37:02.460 --> 00:37:04.251
And so what you can do
is you can take some

00:37:04.251 --> 00:37:06.570
of the things that don't need
to be done synchronously,

00:37:06.570 --> 00:37:08.220
have them done asynchronously.

00:37:08.220 --> 00:37:13.190
So let's say something like
you're going to talk over,

00:37:13.190 --> 00:37:16.400
I don't know, ideas for a new
product or something like that.

00:37:16.400 --> 00:37:17.900
I think that what
you could do is

00:37:17.900 --> 00:37:21.900
you could have people generate
those ideas asynchronously

00:37:21.900 --> 00:37:24.860
and then send them around
and then have the discussion

00:37:24.860 --> 00:37:25.460
synchronously.

00:37:25.460 --> 00:37:27.043
Because a discussion
about those ideas

00:37:27.043 --> 00:37:30.350
is going to be more
valuable synchronously.

00:37:30.350 --> 00:37:32.787
But if you say, OK,
so who has some ideas,

00:37:32.787 --> 00:37:35.120
you're going to have some
people in their absolute worst

00:37:35.120 --> 00:37:35.620
time of day.

00:37:35.620 --> 00:37:38.160
So figure out what you
can do asynchronously.

00:37:38.160 --> 00:37:39.842
And then also spread the pain--

00:37:39.842 --> 00:37:42.050
except if it's your customer,
then you take the pain.

00:37:45.151 --> 00:37:45.650
Who else?

00:37:45.650 --> 00:37:46.150
Yes.

00:37:49.126 --> 00:37:50.500
I have to say,
I'm very impressed

00:37:50.500 --> 00:37:52.875
with the hand-eye coordination
of the people in this room

00:37:52.875 --> 00:37:54.010
today just throughout.

00:37:54.010 --> 00:37:56.781
We have not had a
bobble let alone a drop.

00:37:56.781 --> 00:37:58.780
AUDIENCE: If you have bad
hand-eye coordination,

00:37:58.780 --> 00:38:01.210
you just don't ask
questions with this thing.

00:38:01.210 --> 00:38:02.050
DANIEL PINK: Oh, I
guess that's right.

00:38:02.050 --> 00:38:02.420
We're self-selecting.

00:38:02.420 --> 00:38:03.250
Yeah, well put.

00:38:03.250 --> 00:38:05.800
That's a great point.

00:38:05.800 --> 00:38:08.140
So we're only hearing
questions from people with very

00:38:08.140 --> 00:38:09.910
good hand-eye coordination.

00:38:09.910 --> 00:38:11.870
AUDIENCE: Level of confidence.

00:38:11.870 --> 00:38:14.590
So given the scope of
normal adult day-- which

00:38:14.590 --> 00:38:16.540
is on a weekday, we're working.

00:38:16.540 --> 00:38:18.130
We've got maybe family and kids.

00:38:18.130 --> 00:38:19.000
We've got dinners.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:23.069
We've got maybe some
prayer or meditation time--

00:38:23.069 --> 00:38:24.610
what's the best use
of recovery time?

00:38:24.610 --> 00:38:27.670
If you could structure
your perfect day,

00:38:27.670 --> 00:38:29.349
what tasks or
activities would you

00:38:29.349 --> 00:38:31.390
do during those recovery
periods where we already

00:38:31.390 --> 00:38:34.300
know we're not productive
or mentally sharp?

00:38:34.300 --> 00:38:35.029
DANIEL PINK: OK.

00:38:35.029 --> 00:38:36.570
Yeah, that's an
interesting question.

00:38:36.570 --> 00:38:38.260
So remember, what
we have on mood is

00:38:38.260 --> 00:38:40.455
we have this sort of
peak, trough, recovery.

00:38:40.455 --> 00:38:42.580
Would you consider yourself
more of a morning, more

00:38:42.580 --> 00:38:45.352
of an evening, or in the middle?

00:38:45.352 --> 00:38:46.810
AUDIENCE: Somewhere
in the middle--

00:38:46.810 --> 00:38:49.180
aspiring morning, but
honestly more in the middle.

00:38:49.180 --> 00:38:49.930
DANIEL PINK: Yeah.

00:38:49.930 --> 00:38:52.930
So how would you do on midpoint
of sleep on the question that I

00:38:52.930 --> 00:38:56.551
asked Chris on a free day--
not a day you have to wake up

00:38:56.551 --> 00:38:58.300
to an alarm clock, not
a day you have to--

00:39:01.030 --> 00:39:05.540
AUDIENCE: Right now I'm aiming
for like 10:00 PM to 5:00 AM.

00:39:05.540 --> 00:39:06.740
DANIEL PINK: But not aiming.

00:39:06.740 --> 00:39:07.990
What would you do
naturally if you

00:39:07.990 --> 00:39:10.281
didn't have an aim-- you just
let your body do whatever

00:39:10.281 --> 00:39:11.170
it wanted to do?

00:39:11.170 --> 00:39:12.879
AUDIENCE: Maybe 11:00 to 8:00.

00:39:12.879 --> 00:39:14.170
DANIEL PINK: OK, 11:00 to 8:00.

00:39:14.170 --> 00:39:14.906
So you're--

00:39:14.906 --> 00:39:16.280
AUDIENCE: 11:00
to 7:00, I guess.

00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:16.910
Eight hours.

00:39:16.910 --> 00:39:21.250
DANIEL PINK: So your midpoint
would be 3:00, so you're larky.

00:39:21.250 --> 00:39:23.762
You're more of a
