00:39:33.824 --> 00:39:35.500
So here's what I think about it.

00:39:35.500 --> 00:39:37.950
So recovery-- this is mood--

00:39:37.950 --> 00:39:38.450
peak.

00:39:40.729 --> 00:39:41.770
Did I screw something up?

00:39:41.770 --> 00:39:42.420
OK.

00:39:42.420 --> 00:39:44.211
Here's your mood over
the course of a day--

00:39:44.211 --> 00:39:47.122
peak, trough, recovery.

00:39:47.122 --> 00:39:48.830
So let's talk about
that recovery period,

00:39:48.830 --> 00:39:50.914
because it's a very
interesting period.

00:39:50.914 --> 00:39:53.330
The key in the peak period--
whether it's at the beginning

00:39:53.330 --> 00:39:55.655
of the day, or whether
it begins at 7:00 PM,

00:39:55.655 --> 00:39:58.280
whether it begins at 8:00 in the
morning or 9:00 in the morning

00:39:58.280 --> 00:40:01.340
as it does for me, or whether
it begins at 7:00 PM as it does

00:40:01.340 --> 00:40:02.210
for Chris--

00:40:02.210 --> 00:40:04.280
the key aspect of
the peak is this.

00:40:04.280 --> 00:40:06.590
That's when we
are most vigilant.

00:40:06.590 --> 00:40:08.480
Vigilance is the key point here.

00:40:08.480 --> 00:40:10.760
Vigilance means we're able
to bat away distractions.

00:40:10.760 --> 00:40:13.910
That makes it a good time for
the heads down, locked down,

00:40:13.910 --> 00:40:15.070
analytic kinds of work.

00:40:15.070 --> 00:40:17.570
The recovery period is actually
a really interesting period,

00:40:17.570 --> 00:40:18.860
because here's what happens.

00:40:18.860 --> 00:40:22.670
Our mood goes back up,
but we're less vigilant.

00:40:22.670 --> 00:40:27.260
And that ends up being actually
an interesting combination.

00:40:27.260 --> 00:40:30.144
Think about brainstorming,
for instance.

00:40:30.144 --> 00:40:32.060
I'm sure you've been in
brainstorming sessions

00:40:32.060 --> 00:40:33.320
where someone says,
that's a bad idea.

00:40:33.320 --> 00:40:34.280
That's a bad idea.

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:36.590
They're hyper-vigilant,
hyper-analytical,

00:40:36.590 --> 00:40:39.332
and so they're knocking
down anything that's wobbly.

00:40:39.332 --> 00:40:40.790
But for brainstorming,
you actually

00:40:40.790 --> 00:40:42.290
want a little bit
of disinhibition.

00:40:42.290 --> 00:40:43.970
You don't want super-vigilance.

00:40:43.970 --> 00:40:46.520
And so it turns out that
there's certain kinds

00:40:46.520 --> 00:40:48.500
of problem solving--

00:40:48.500 --> 00:40:50.870
certain kinds of non-obvious
problem solving--

00:40:50.870 --> 00:40:55.490
that people do better
in that recovery period

00:40:55.490 --> 00:40:58.292
which we look at as kind
of a non-optimal period.

00:40:58.292 --> 00:41:00.500
You want your locked down,
important, heads down work

00:41:00.500 --> 00:41:02.270
during your peak, but
there's an advantage

00:41:02.270 --> 00:41:03.470
to that recovery period.

00:41:03.470 --> 00:41:06.050
You have elevated
mood, less vigilance.

00:41:06.050 --> 00:41:08.840
You have some disinhibition,
and you're feeling OK.

00:41:08.840 --> 00:41:11.330
Brainstorming, iterative work--

00:41:11.330 --> 00:41:15.246
I end up doing a lot
of my interviews--

00:41:15.246 --> 00:41:17.870
so when I'm interviewing people
for books and things like that,

00:41:17.870 --> 00:41:18.828
because my interviews--

00:41:18.828 --> 00:41:20.480
I'm not an
investigative reporter.

00:41:20.480 --> 00:41:21.770
I'm not taking a deposition.

00:41:21.770 --> 00:41:24.590
I'm not trying to trap people
in contradictions or anything

00:41:24.590 --> 00:41:25.092
like that.

00:41:25.092 --> 00:41:27.300
My interviews are, hey, what
do you think about this?

00:41:27.300 --> 00:41:28.508
What do you think about that?

00:41:28.508 --> 00:41:30.920
Does that make any sense--
much sort of yeastier.

00:41:30.920 --> 00:41:33.320
And I find I do those
interviews better.

00:41:33.320 --> 00:41:36.060
I find I do my
locked down writing--

00:41:36.060 --> 00:41:38.120
making the words march
in order on the page--

00:41:38.120 --> 00:41:41.300
in the morning and then the
looser stuff later in the day

00:41:41.300 --> 00:41:44.560
during that recovery period.

00:41:44.560 --> 00:41:46.924
Yes.

00:41:46.924 --> 00:41:48.340
I don't even know
if we need this.

00:41:51.580 --> 00:41:53.080
AUDIENCE: I was
wondering if there's

00:41:53.080 --> 00:41:55.810
been any work done
to help, for example,

00:41:55.810 --> 00:41:58.210
the judges or the
anesthesiologists

00:41:58.210 --> 00:42:02.610
perform better their
drops or act more fairly.

00:42:02.610 --> 00:42:04.117
Do you just take more breaks?

00:42:04.117 --> 00:42:05.200
What's the solution there?

00:42:05.200 --> 00:42:06.470
DANIEL PINK: That's part of it.

00:42:06.470 --> 00:42:08.011
It's a really, really
great question.

00:42:13.610 --> 00:42:16.070
At some level, there are two
different kinds of breaks.

00:42:16.070 --> 00:42:18.876
One of them is a
restorative break,

00:42:18.876 --> 00:42:20.750
and that's the kind of
breaks that most of us

00:42:20.750 --> 00:42:22.650
should be taking at work.

00:42:22.650 --> 00:42:26.550
So we should be going out
in the afternoon to take--

00:42:26.550 --> 00:42:29.460
we know a lot about breaks.

00:42:29.460 --> 00:42:31.460
Basically, my view is
that the science of breaks

00:42:31.460 --> 00:42:33.540
is where the science of
sleep was 15 years ago.

00:42:33.540 --> 00:42:37.530
15 years ago here at
Alphabet-- or Google

00:42:37.530 --> 00:42:39.290
then-- writ large,
people who pulled

00:42:39.290 --> 00:42:40.549
all-nighters were heroes.

00:42:40.549 --> 00:42:42.590
And now we know a lot
about the science of sleep,

00:42:42.590 --> 00:42:43.160
and we say, no.

00:42:43.160 --> 00:42:44.540
You're not a hero if
you pull an all-nighter.

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:45.360
You're an idiot.

00:42:45.360 --> 00:42:46.250
You're hurting your performance.

00:42:46.250 --> 00:42:47.874
You're probably
hurting the performance

00:42:47.874 --> 00:42:49.271
of people you're working with.

00:42:49.271 --> 00:42:51.770
I think the science of breaks
are where the science of sleep

00:42:51.770 --> 00:42:53.000
was 15 years ago.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:55.041
We should be taking more
breaks, and we should be

00:42:55.041 --> 00:42:57.290
taking certain kinds of breaks.

00:42:57.290 --> 00:43:01.070
So part of it is actually
in some of this more breaks,

00:43:01.070 --> 00:43:03.320
and we should be taking these
certain kinds of breaks.

00:43:03.320 --> 00:43:06.290
We should be taking
breaks where we're

00:43:06.290 --> 00:43:07.980
moving rather than stationary.

00:43:07.980 --> 00:43:10.700
We should be taking them
outside rather than inside.

00:43:10.700 --> 00:43:13.500
We know from the research
that social beats solo

00:43:13.500 --> 00:43:16.010
in break taking, so take a
break with somebody else.

00:43:16.010 --> 00:43:17.385
And we know the
importance-- this

00:43:17.385 --> 00:43:19.357
is urgent-- of full detachment.

00:43:19.357 --> 00:43:21.440
So when you take a break,
leave your phone behind.

00:43:21.440 --> 00:43:22.790
Don't talk about work.

00:43:22.790 --> 00:43:25.400
So if you were to
start a regimen where

00:43:25.400 --> 00:43:26.750
twice an afternoon--

00:43:26.750 --> 00:43:29.390
once an afternoon-- you
took a 10 or 15 minute break

00:43:29.390 --> 00:43:32.282
outside, take a walk outside
with someone you like,

00:43:32.282 --> 00:43:34.490
leaving your phone behind
and talking about something

00:43:34.490 --> 00:43:36.850
other than work,
I'm convinced it

00:43:36.850 --> 00:43:38.210
will be a performance booster.

00:43:38.210 --> 00:43:44.710
Now, another kind of break
is a vigilance break.

00:43:44.710 --> 00:43:48.880
And so what you see in
medicine is the following.

00:43:48.880 --> 00:43:51.004
So the stakes are a
little bit higher.

00:43:51.004 --> 00:43:52.670
Stakes are a little
bit higher if you're

00:43:52.670 --> 00:43:55.190
talking about life and
death or human liberty.

00:43:55.190 --> 00:43:57.290
And there what you do--

00:43:57.290 --> 00:43:58.820
and I write about this.

00:43:58.820 --> 00:44:01.160
Go to the University of
Michigan Medical Center,

00:44:01.160 --> 00:44:04.400
and they're about to do a
surgery in the afternoon.

00:44:04.400 --> 00:44:08.450
And before they even begin the
surgery, they take a time out.

00:44:08.450 --> 00:44:12.740
And everybody-- the surgeon, the
nurses, the anesthesiologists--

00:44:12.740 --> 00:44:15.150
take a step back.

00:44:15.150 --> 00:44:19.480
They take a break,
look at the checklist,

00:44:19.480 --> 00:44:21.002
go over everything again.

00:44:21.002 --> 00:44:22.960
They basically have a
check on their vigilance.

00:44:22.960 --> 00:44:24.160
They don't go right in.

00:44:27.110 --> 00:44:29.350
So a way to mitigate
a lot of that

00:44:29.350 --> 00:44:32.740
is a vigilance break
for those high stakes

00:44:32.740 --> 00:44:35.440
kinds of encounters
where before you begin,

00:44:35.440 --> 00:44:36.580
you take a step back.

00:44:39.350 --> 00:44:40.840
You go back and
say, I know I'm not

00:44:40.840 --> 00:44:42.650
at my vigilance best right now.

00:44:42.650 --> 00:44:44.233
So what I want to
do is I want to take

00:44:44.233 --> 00:44:47.650
a step back and actually go
through a list and figure out,

00:44:47.650 --> 00:44:48.964
am I following the procedures?

00:44:48.964 --> 00:44:50.380
Am I doing everything
I need to do

00:44:50.380 --> 00:44:53.560
to be as vigilant as possible?

00:44:53.560 --> 00:44:56.641
I actually think there's a good
argument for judges doing that.

00:44:56.641 --> 00:44:58.390
Because I don't think
it's simply a case--

00:44:58.390 --> 00:45:01.090
I don't want to rely on
a justice system that--

00:45:01.090 --> 00:45:02.980
I don't want the justice
system to hinge on

00:45:02.980 --> 00:45:05.170
whether the judge has
a walk in the park.

00:45:07.750 --> 00:45:09.920
And so I think there's
ways to do that.

00:45:09.920 --> 00:45:13.740
In fact, there are a lot
of moves to actually--

00:45:13.740 --> 00:45:15.490
for sentencing and
those kinds of things--

00:45:15.490 --> 00:45:19.550
to turn it into a sort of
almost algorithmic sentencing.

00:45:19.550 --> 00:45:24.650
So there's a script
that we use for that,

00:45:24.650 --> 00:45:27.721
but I think that vigilance
breaks for judges

00:45:27.721 --> 00:45:29.050
would be a big deal.

00:45:29.050 --> 00:45:31.600
And so you could
say something like,

00:45:31.600 --> 00:45:33.340
I'm about to make
a decision here.

00:45:33.340 --> 00:45:35.920
Am I treating this
like a comparable--

00:45:35.920 --> 00:45:39.200
what have I done in
comparable cases?

00:45:39.200 --> 00:45:41.777
What have I done for
comparable kinds of things?

00:45:41.777 --> 00:45:43.360
And they take a step
back and actually

00:45:43.360 --> 00:45:44.985
make sure they're
being vigilant rather

00:45:44.985 --> 00:45:49.030
than just being a hostage
of the diurnal patterns.

00:45:49.030 --> 00:45:50.727
Do we have one more, two more?

00:45:50.727 --> 00:45:52.810
AUDIENCE: I wonder if we
have any similar problems

00:45:52.810 --> 00:45:54.390
with interviewing
here or elsewhere.

00:45:54.390 --> 00:45:55.710
DANIEL PINK: Absolutely.

00:45:55.710 --> 00:45:58.130
There's absolutely no
question about that.

00:45:58.130 --> 00:46:00.850
There's no question
that there's going

00:46:00.850 --> 00:46:02.740
to be time of day
bias introduced

00:46:02.740 --> 00:46:03.840
in anything like that.

00:46:03.840 --> 00:46:06.160
In interviewing-- no question.

00:46:06.160 --> 00:46:08.680
In reading college
admissions files--

00:46:08.680 --> 00:46:09.880
no question.

00:46:13.150 --> 00:46:16.510
Remember, axiomatic--
our cognitive abilities

00:46:16.510 --> 00:46:18.350
don't say the same
throughout the day.

00:46:18.350 --> 00:46:20.510
Our mood doesn't stay the
same throughout the day.

00:46:20.510 --> 00:46:22.390
Our decision making
capacities don't stay the same

00:46:22.390 --> 00:46:23.290
throughout the day.

00:46:23.290 --> 00:46:25.090
So there are going to be--

00:46:25.090 --> 00:46:28.160
now, you guys do multiple
interviews with people.

00:46:28.160 --> 00:46:31.400
So your candidates will
interview with multiple people.

00:46:31.400 --> 00:46:34.450
So you might be able to actually
tease that out of the system

00:46:34.450 --> 00:46:36.420
by having enough
variation so that--

00:46:36.420 --> 00:46:39.249
OK, so every candidate's
going to have some afternoon

00:46:39.249 --> 00:46:41.290
interviews, some evening
interviews, some morning

00:46:41.290 --> 00:46:41.710
interviews.

00:46:41.710 --> 00:46:44.020
And so you might actually be
able to even it out that way.

00:46:44.020 --> 00:46:45.394
There's no question
there's going

00:46:45.394 --> 00:46:47.770
to be bias in any kind
of human encounter based

00:46:47.770 --> 00:46:49.990
on time of day, period.

00:46:49.990 --> 00:46:53.260
AUDIENCE: So I actually
had a question about when

00:46:53.260 --> 00:46:54.995
you should do fun things.

00:46:54.995 --> 00:46:55.870
When will you enjoy--

00:46:55.870 --> 00:46:56.661
DANIEL PINK: Don't.

00:46:56.661 --> 00:46:58.362
AUDIENCE: --fun things more?

00:46:58.362 --> 00:46:59.320
DANIEL PINK: You won't.

00:46:59.320 --> 00:47:01.240
No, give me an example.

00:47:01.240 --> 00:47:04.450
AUDIENCE: Well,
like socializing.

00:47:04.450 --> 00:47:08.680
Sometimes you feel like you
have a better time with friends

00:47:08.680 --> 00:47:12.000
or sometimes you're
more frustrated.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:19.180
What times are good to bond
with friends or strangers more?

00:47:19.180 --> 00:47:21.150
DANIEL PINK: I think
what you see is--

00:47:21.150 --> 00:47:24.694
well, I don't want to recommend
bonding with strangers

00:47:24.694 --> 00:47:26.860
in all cases-- just want
to say that for the record.

00:47:30.370 --> 00:47:31.910
As a father, I don't-- you know.

00:47:34.490 --> 00:47:37.090
So if we look at the pattern
of mood again, what you see

00:47:37.090 --> 00:47:42.410
is there's some chicken
and egg effect here.

00:47:42.410 --> 00:47:44.770
So remember-- peak,
trough, recovery.

00:47:44.770 --> 00:47:47.110
And in the evenings,
our mood is--

00:47:50.200 --> 00:47:55.150
for the 80% of us who have
that more traditional kind

00:47:55.150 --> 00:47:55.870
of pattern--

00:47:55.870 --> 00:47:58.330
our moods in the evenings
are actually pretty good.

00:47:58.330 --> 00:48:02.875
And so it's a little
chicken and egg,

00:48:02.875 --> 00:48:04.240
and it's hard to disentangle.

00:48:04.240 --> 00:48:06.310
Our moods could be good because
we're more likely to socialize,

00:48:06.310 --> 00:48:08.530
but it could also be that
we're more likely to socialize

00:48:08.530 --> 00:48:09.655
because our moods are good.

00:48:12.280 --> 00:48:13.760
I think that's
the time to do it.

00:48:13.760 --> 00:48:15.635
But there's some really,
really good research

00:48:15.635 --> 00:48:21.510
out there irrespective
of timing on friendship

00:48:21.510 --> 00:48:24.160
and what are the elements
of maintaining friendships?

00:48:24.160 --> 00:48:29.830
And I can't think of the name
of the book, but what it shows

00:48:29.830 --> 00:48:34.870
is that making and
maintaining friendships

00:48:34.870 --> 00:48:38.710
is actually much harder
than we realized.

00:48:38.710 --> 00:48:40.540
It requires two things
that we're often

00:48:40.540 --> 00:48:41.414
not comfortable with.

00:48:41.414 --> 00:48:43.690
Number one-- it requires a
significant amount of time.

00:48:43.690 --> 00:48:48.280
There's no instant-- you
have to put in the time

00:48:48.280 --> 00:48:50.500
if you really want to have
an enduring friendship.

00:48:50.500 --> 00:48:54.790
The other thing-- which is a
reason why men often don't have

00:48:54.790 --> 00:48:57.730
as many or as rich friendships
as women talking about broad

00:48:57.730 --> 00:49:00.910
populations-- is that the
research on friendship--

00:49:00.910 --> 00:49:02.950
you've got to devote
the time to it.

00:49:02.950 --> 00:49:08.920
The second thing is the
importance of self-disclosure.

00:49:08.920 --> 00:49:12.010
Self-disclosure ends up
being this incredible bonding

00:49:12.010 --> 00:49:15.870
agent for friendships.

00:49:15.870 --> 00:49:17.874
I mean, I hate
self-disclosure, and that's

00:49:17.874 --> 00:49:18.790
why I have no friends.

00:49:24.076 --> 00:49:25.450
To answer your
question directly,

00:49:25.450 --> 00:49:27.040
mood is better in the evening.

00:49:27.040 --> 00:49:28.870
That's probably a good time.

00:49:28.870 --> 00:49:31.000
And there's a huge
amount of research

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:33.310
on the importance of
friendships and relationships

00:49:33.310 --> 00:49:35.380
to our overall well being.

00:49:35.380 --> 00:49:38.270
The challenge, as I said, is
that it requires devoting time.

00:49:38.270 --> 00:49:40.072
It really does.

00:49:40.072 --> 00:49:42.280
And it requires self-disclosure,
and that's something

00:49:42.280 --> 00:49:43.970
that a lot of us,
myself included,

00:49:43.970 --> 00:49:45.520
are a little bit leery of.

00:49:45.520 --> 00:49:47.740
Let's take one more,
and then we'll wrap up.

00:49:47.740 --> 00:49:48.730
AUDIENCE: This is going to
sound like a joke question,

00:49:48.730 --> 00:49:50.564
but where does coffee
play into all of this?

00:49:50.564 --> 00:49:52.230
DANIEL PINK: That's
not a joke question.

00:49:52.230 --> 00:49:53.590
That's a very serious question.

00:49:53.590 --> 00:49:56.140
AUDIENCE: Does it change
those energy patterns?

00:49:56.140 --> 00:49:58.210
If you have an important
meeting with someone,

00:49:58.210 --> 00:50:01.822
how smart is it to say, it
should be a coffee meeting.

00:50:01.822 --> 00:50:04.030
Because then you can ensure
everybody's energy levels

00:50:04.030 --> 00:50:05.754
will be spiked.

00:50:05.754 --> 00:50:08.170
DANIEL PINK: There's going to
be some individual variation

00:50:08.170 --> 00:50:14.147
on that, but the positive
benefits of caffeine up

00:50:14.147 --> 00:50:14.980
to a certain limit--

00:50:14.980 --> 00:50:16.330
I mean, not going crazy--

00:50:16.330 --> 00:50:17.800
are very high.

00:50:20.790 --> 00:50:23.154
And so what you also have--

00:50:23.154 --> 00:50:24.820
just remember, it
takes a certain amount

00:50:24.820 --> 00:50:27.028
of time for the caffeine to
get into the bloodstream.

00:50:31.440 --> 00:50:35.500
If you and I sit down and
begin to have a cup of coffee,

00:50:35.500 --> 00:50:40.080
the caffeine's not going to hit
our bloodstream for 25 minutes.

00:50:40.080 --> 00:50:42.190
It depends on how long
our meeting's going to be.

00:50:42.190 --> 00:50:44.060
So what it could be is that you
and I have a crappy meeting,

00:50:44.060 --> 00:50:45.934
and then my meeting with
this guy a half hour

00:50:45.934 --> 00:50:47.440
later is awesome thanks to you.

00:50:55.540 --> 00:50:57.790
The effects of caffeine,
obviously, are ephemeral.

00:50:57.790 --> 00:51:00.970
There are two caffeine
tips that are in the book.

00:51:00.970 --> 00:51:02.590
One of them is this.

00:51:02.590 --> 00:51:06.310
You're better off not
having caffeine immediately

00:51:06.310 --> 00:51:08.160
when you wake up--

00:51:08.160 --> 00:51:09.822
immediately when you wake up.

00:51:09.822 --> 00:51:11.655
When we wake up we begin
producing cortisol.

00:51:11.655 --> 00:51:12.630
It's a stress hormone.

00:51:12.630 --> 00:51:15.480
That's how we wake
up in some ways.

00:51:15.480 --> 00:51:17.010
We have this hormone coming.

00:51:17.010 --> 00:51:18.360
Wake up, wake up, wake up.

00:51:18.360 --> 00:51:21.440
So we start producing this
stress hormone of cortisol.

00:51:21.440 --> 00:51:24.090
Our cortisol levels
rise as we wake up,

00:51:24.090 --> 00:51:27.120
and caffeine
actually can inhibit

00:51:27.120 --> 00:51:28.900
the production of cortisol.

00:51:28.900 --> 00:51:31.950
And so if you have coffee
when you first wake up,

00:51:31.950 --> 00:51:33.810
you're really not gaining much.

00:51:33.810 --> 00:51:36.690
What you're better off doing is
waiting about an hour after you

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:41.340
wake up when your cortisol
levels begin to drop

00:51:41.340 --> 00:51:43.030
and then hit it
with the caffeine.

00:51:43.030 --> 00:51:44.404
That's something
that I've tried.

00:51:44.404 --> 00:51:46.904
That's something that
I've tried to do.

00:51:46.904 --> 00:51:48.570
There are other people
who I'm convinced

00:51:48.570 --> 00:51:53.029
have basically a conditioned
psychological response

00:51:53.029 --> 00:51:54.570
to coffee first
thing in the morning.

00:51:54.570 --> 00:51:56.825
That is, you could
probably switch out decaf.

00:51:56.825 --> 00:51:58.950
And what they're responding
to is not the caffeine,

00:51:58.950 --> 00:52:00.914
but they're responding
to the ritual.

00:52:00.914 --> 00:52:01.830
I'm convinced of that.

00:52:01.830 --> 00:52:05.190
Now, another good use of
caffeine is the following.

00:52:05.190 --> 00:52:06.981
Do you guys have nap pods here?

00:52:06.981 --> 00:52:07.480
OK.

00:52:07.480 --> 00:52:10.240
So anybody ever use them?

00:52:10.240 --> 00:52:10.740
No.

00:52:10.740 --> 00:52:12.560
All right.

00:52:12.560 --> 00:52:13.990
So here's how to use it.

00:52:13.990 --> 00:52:16.060
Here's how to take
the ideal nap.

00:52:16.060 --> 00:52:17.170
Here's what you do.

00:52:17.170 --> 00:52:19.420
The ideal nap it turns
out is very, very short--

00:52:19.420 --> 00:52:21.670
between 10 and 20 minutes long--

00:52:21.670 --> 00:52:23.520
much shorter than I
would have expected.

00:52:23.520 --> 00:52:25.780
10 and 20 minutes is
the ideal length nap--

00:52:25.780 --> 00:52:27.499
gets you that restoration
without what's

00:52:27.499 --> 00:52:29.290
called sleep inertia,
which is that groggy,

00:52:29.290 --> 00:52:31.870
boggy feeling that you
get when you take a nap.

00:52:31.870 --> 00:52:34.270
So the ideal nap-- what I
do in my office is this.

00:52:37.490 --> 00:52:39.940
I sit in a chair in my office.

00:52:39.940 --> 00:52:42.730
I will put on noise
canceling headphones.

00:52:42.730 --> 00:52:47.230
I'll set my timer on my
phone for 25 minutes,

00:52:47.230 --> 00:52:50.210
and I can usually fall asleep
in about 10 or 12 minutes.

00:52:50.210 --> 00:52:55.210
And so that gives me
a 14, 15 minute nap,

00:52:55.210 --> 00:52:57.910
which is ideal, because
the alarm goes off

00:52:57.910 --> 00:52:59.150
after 25 minutes.

00:52:59.150 --> 00:53:03.230
But before I turn on the
timer or close my eyes,

00:53:03.230 --> 00:53:06.780
I down a cup of
coffee before the nap.

00:53:06.780 --> 00:53:08.400
And so what happens
is the following.

00:53:08.400 --> 00:53:12.460
I wake up with that
ideal short nap restored,

00:53:12.460 --> 00:53:14.455
but it takes 25 minutes
for the caffeine

00:53:14.455 --> 00:53:15.580
to get into my bloodstream.

00:53:15.580 --> 00:53:18.610
So when I'm waking up, I get
hit with that second boost

00:53:18.610 --> 00:53:19.990
of caffeine.

00:53:19.990 --> 00:53:21.815
And it's something
called a "nappuccino."

00:53:24.826 --> 00:53:26.200
There are actually
several papers

00:53:26.200 --> 00:53:30.340
on this showing its
efficacy believe it or not.

00:53:30.340 --> 00:53:32.050
You had a question
here in the front row?

00:53:32.050 --> 00:53:35.207
AUDIENCE: My question was,
it all seems like the topic--

00:53:35.207 --> 00:53:36.790
I'll reflect back
what you just said--

00:53:36.790 --> 00:53:41.020
is the "when" depends
on freshness of mind.

00:53:41.020 --> 00:53:45.864
Is there any other major
causal factor of to when?

00:53:45.864 --> 00:53:47.030
DANIEL PINK: Oh, absolutely.

00:53:47.030 --> 00:53:47.360
Yeah.

00:53:47.360 --> 00:53:48.485
So that's a great question.

00:53:48.485 --> 00:53:50.752
So some of it is on the
judges-- this is speculation

00:53:50.752 --> 00:53:51.710
in the judges research.

00:53:51.710 --> 00:53:54.529
Some of it has to do with-- it
could be with glucose levels.

00:53:54.529 --> 00:53:56.570
Another big factor,
especially in physical stuff,

00:53:56.570 --> 00:53:58.280
is body temperature.

00:53:58.280 --> 00:54:02.080
Body temperature has a
surprisingly large role

00:54:02.080 --> 00:54:03.426
in our--

00:54:03.426 --> 00:54:05.300
not surprising-- in our
physical performance.

00:54:05.300 --> 00:54:08.060
So this is one
reason why if you're

00:54:08.060 --> 00:54:09.412
deciding whether to exercise--

00:54:09.412 --> 00:54:11.870
what time of day to exercise--
there are virtues of morning

00:54:11.870 --> 00:54:13.040
exercise big time.

00:54:13.040 --> 00:54:15.400
It's better for habit formation,
better for weight loss.

00:54:15.400 --> 00:54:18.950
There are virtues for afternoon
and evening exercise, too.

00:54:18.950 --> 00:54:21.045
Because around
4:00 to 7:00 or so,

00:54:21.045 --> 00:54:22.670
our body temperature
is at its highest.

00:54:22.670 --> 00:54:26.600
So afternoon exercise-- you're
less likely to get injured.

00:54:26.600 --> 00:54:27.980
Fewer injuries then.

00:54:27.980 --> 00:54:31.580
Afternoon exercise-- people
find it less effortful,

00:54:31.580 --> 00:54:34.400
and so that can aid
in habit formation.

00:54:34.400 --> 00:54:37.070
And actually, our
performance is better, too.

00:54:37.070 --> 00:54:40.490
Hand-eye coordination improves,
so coming here at 6:00

00:54:40.490 --> 00:54:41.540
would be amazing.

00:54:41.540 --> 00:54:43.850
Hand-eye coordination improves,
lung function improves,

00:54:43.850 --> 00:54:44.526
speed improves.

00:54:44.526 --> 00:54:46.400
So there's actually a
disproportionate number

00:54:46.400 --> 00:54:49.040
of records and speed events
that were set between 4:00

00:54:49.040 --> 00:54:50.750
PM and 7:00 PM local time.

00:54:50.750 --> 00:54:55.940
So body temperature really
surprised me as a driver

00:54:55.940 --> 00:54:56.900
behind that.

00:54:56.900 --> 00:55:00.220
Our bodies and brains
are very complex systems,

00:55:00.220 --> 00:55:01.490
so some of it's hormonal.

00:55:01.490 --> 00:55:03.840
Some of it is body temperature.

00:55:03.840 --> 00:55:05.930
Some of it is purely cognitive.

00:55:05.930 --> 00:55:07.310
Some of it is neurochemical.

00:55:07.310 --> 00:55:12.840
I mean, these are
exquisitely complex systems,

00:55:12.840 --> 00:55:16.397
so it's hard to disentangle what
exactly every causal agent is.

00:55:16.397 --> 00:55:18.230
Let's go one more, then
we'll wrap up-- back

00:55:18.230 --> 00:55:23.830
in the left field bleachers
or right field bleachers.

00:55:23.830 --> 00:55:25.580
AUDIENCE: We've talked
a lot about time of

00:55:25.580 --> 00:55:27.410
day, but how about time of year?

00:55:27.410 --> 00:55:30.470
One question is, have you
studied optimal time of year

00:55:30.470 --> 00:55:33.764
to take a vacation for a
company's maximum productivity?

00:55:33.764 --> 00:55:35.180
I know some people
kind of scatter

00:55:35.180 --> 00:55:36.410
out their vacation days.

00:55:36.410 --> 00:55:38.210
Some people save
them for holidays.

00:55:38.210 --> 00:55:40.109
Based on your research,
I assume if you're

00:55:40.109 --> 00:55:42.650
most productive at the start of
a quarter, start of the year,

00:55:42.650 --> 00:55:46.555
then maybe it would be
middle of a quarter.

00:55:46.555 --> 00:55:47.930
DANIEL PINK: Part
of the question

00:55:47.930 --> 00:55:51.080
is just observing
your own behavior

00:55:51.080 --> 00:55:52.659
and seeing what works for you.

00:55:52.659 --> 00:55:54.200
I don't write about
this in the book,

00:55:54.200 --> 00:55:56.850
but did I have looked at
the research on vacations

00:55:56.850 --> 00:55:58.450
for something else.

00:55:58.450 --> 00:56:03.330
The restorative effects of
vacations are significant.

00:56:03.330 --> 00:56:06.720
They're very fleeting.

00:56:06.720 --> 00:56:07.290
It's sad.

00:56:07.290 --> 00:56:09.820
They really don't
last for that long.

00:56:09.820 --> 00:56:13.320
And so there's an argument
for taking more shorter ones

00:56:13.320 --> 00:56:15.240
than some longer ones.

00:56:15.240 --> 00:56:16.672
It's going to depend, OK?

00:56:16.672 --> 00:56:18.130
There's so many
variables in there.

00:56:18.130 --> 00:56:19.950
It depends on your
family situation.

00:56:19.950 --> 00:56:22.830
It depends on maybe where
you are in your career.

00:56:22.830 --> 00:56:25.050
It depends on all
kinds of things.

00:56:25.050 --> 00:56:27.510
But vacations have
a positive effect

00:56:27.510 --> 00:56:31.230
on restoring mood,
focus, clear thinking,

00:56:31.230 --> 00:56:34.420
but the effects are
shockingly short-lived.

00:56:34.420 --> 00:56:37.590
I mean, it's really
sad how short-lived

00:56:37.590 --> 00:56:38.460
those things can be.

00:56:38.460 --> 00:56:45.480
As for time of year,
there's something

00:56:45.480 --> 00:56:49.740
to be said for taking a vacation
or taking some kind of break

00:56:49.740 --> 00:56:54.540
or something like that
at a midpoint of a year,

00:56:54.540 --> 00:56:58.110
because midpoints have this
effect on getting our attention

00:56:58.110 --> 00:56:59.400
and galvanizing us.

00:57:05.970 --> 00:57:09.600
Here the design principles
are less distinct and clear.

00:57:09.600 --> 00:57:12.390
I think you have to experiment
a little bit with yourself.

00:57:12.390 --> 00:57:17.580
But I do think that there's
a solid argument for fewer,

00:57:17.580 --> 00:57:21.270
shorter vacations just because
the effects of the vacation

00:57:21.270 --> 00:57:24.459
are so ephemeral.

00:57:24.459 --> 00:57:25.750
Let me just say one more thing.

00:57:25.750 --> 00:57:27.090
So tell me your first name.

00:57:27.090 --> 00:57:27.820
AUDIENCE: David.

00:57:27.820 --> 00:57:28.200
DANIEL PINK: David?

00:57:28.200 --> 00:57:29.950
So David's question
is actually a good way

00:57:29.950 --> 00:57:31.900
to end in that what
David's talking about

00:57:31.900 --> 00:57:33.900
are two things that are
really, really important

00:57:33.900 --> 00:57:36.580
in this overall body of work.

00:57:36.580 --> 00:57:41.490
One of them is asking
the right questions

00:57:41.490 --> 00:57:45.340
and observing our own behavior,
which I mentioned before.

00:57:45.340 --> 00:57:47.550
The other one is
being intentional.

00:57:47.550 --> 00:57:49.440
And one of the
things that we don't

00:57:49.440 --> 00:57:51.360
do a very good job
of-- especially when it

00:57:51.360 --> 00:57:54.570
comes to temporal things--
is being intentional.

00:57:54.570 --> 00:57:56.490
And so if you look at today--

00:57:56.490 --> 00:57:59.190
anybody here have a to-do list?

00:57:59.190 --> 00:58:01.601
That's intentionality
right there.

00:58:01.601 --> 00:58:04.100
You're being very intentional
about what you're going to do.

00:58:04.100 --> 00:58:05.410
We're intentional about
what we're going to do.

00:58:05.410 --> 00:58:07.530
We're intentional about
who we're going to do it.

00:58:07.530 --> 00:58:10.452
So we have at Google
rounds of interviews.

00:58:10.452 --> 00:58:12.160
We're intentional
about how we do things.

00:58:12.160 --> 00:58:15.702
But when it comes to
when we do things,

00:58:15.702 --> 00:58:16.910
we're not intentional at all.

00:58:16.910 --> 00:58:18.610
You see it in meetings.

00:58:18.610 --> 00:58:19.930
How do we schedule meetings?

00:58:19.930 --> 00:58:21.090
We use only one criterion.

00:58:21.090 --> 00:58:24.310
What criterion do we use
in scheduling meetings?

00:58:24.310 --> 00:58:25.195
Availability.

00:58:25.195 --> 00:58:27.070
Are the people available,
the room available?

00:58:27.070 --> 00:58:29.140
We don't say, what kind
of work are we doing?

00:58:29.140 --> 00:58:30.860
Are they morning people
doing this thing?

00:58:30.860 --> 00:58:32.380
Are they afternoon
people doing this thing?

00:58:32.380 --> 00:58:33.490
Is it a purely administrative?

00:58:33.490 --> 00:58:34.390
We don't think about that.

00:58:34.390 --> 00:58:35.570
It's all about availability.

00:58:35.570 --> 00:58:36.945
We're not intentional
about that.

00:58:36.945 --> 00:58:39.430
So if we observe our own
behavior and are intentional

00:58:39.430 --> 00:58:41.530
and we recognize that we
are temporal creatures

00:58:41.530 --> 00:58:43.720
in a temporal world,
I really think

00:58:43.720 --> 00:58:46.550
that it can be a big boost
to your overall well being

00:58:46.550 --> 00:58:50.380
and a big boost to your
productivity and creativity.

00:58:50.380 --> 00:58:50.980
Thank you.

